06242nam a22009255i 9783110197426DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20092004gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831101974267 a10.1515/97831101974262doi  a(DE-B1597)32213  a(OCoLC)979970864  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aGR366b.A87 2004eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a398/.089/99152221 aKlapproth, Danièle M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNarrative as Social Practice :bAnglo-Western and Australian Aboriginal Oral Traditions /cDanièle M. Klapproth. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (456 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage, Power and Social Process [LPSP] ,x1861-4175 ;v1300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tPart One. In the web of the wor(l)d: The narrative structuring of experience -- tChapter 2. Creating webs of significace: The role of narrative in socio-cultural construction of reality -- tChapter 3. The narrative sharing of words: Storytelling as communicative interaction -- tChapter 4. Exploring the structure of narrated worlds: The search for study schemata -- tPart Two. Storytelling as social practice: A cross-cultural perspective -- tChapter 5. The Beautiful and the Beasty: Cultural specifics of Anglo-Western narrative aesthetics -- tChapter 6. Always keeping track: Text building strategies in Pitjantjatjara and Yankunyjatjara storytelling -- tChapter 7. Holding the world in place: The interrelatedness of story, practice, and culture -- tChapter 8. Conclusions and implications -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNarrative as Social Practice sets out to explore the complex and fascinating interrelatedness of narrative and culture. It does so by contrasting the oral storytelling traditions of two widely divergent cultures - Anglo-Western culture and the Central Australian culture of the Pitjantjatjara/Yankunytjatjara Aborigines. Combining discourse-analytical and pragmalinguistic methodologies with the perspectives of ethnopoetics and the ethnography of communication, this book presents a highly original and engaging study of storytelling as a vital communicative activity at the heart of socio-cultural life. The book is concerned with both theoretical and empirical issues. It engages critically with the theoretical framework of social constructivism and the notion of social practice, and it offers critical discussions of the most influential theories of narrative put forward in Western thinking. Arguing for the adoption of a communication-oriented and cross-cultural perspective as a prerequisite for improving our understanding of the cultural variability of narrative practice, Klapproth presents detailed textual analyses of Anglo-Western and Australian Aboriginal oral narratives, and contextualizes them with respect to the different storytelling practices, values and worldviews in both cultures. Narrative as Social Practice offers new insights to students and specialists in the fields of narratology, discourse analysis, cross-cultural pragmatics, anthropology, folklore study, the ethnography of communication, and Australian Aboriginal studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAboriginal AustraliansvFolklore. 0aDiscourse analysis, NarrativezAustralia. 0aOral traditionzAustralia. 0aOral traditionzEnglish-speaking countries. 4aAustralien. 4aErzählen. 4aGesprochene Sprache. 4aSprachsoziologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAustralia.  aSociology of Language.  aSpoken Language.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert